{"id":"1512.03827","submitter":"Yeinzon Rodriguez Garcia Prof.","authors":"Yeinzon Rodriguez (Universidad Antonio Narino, Universidad Industrial\n  de Santander, The Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics)","title":"A New Pedagogical Way of Finding Out the Gauge Field Strength Tensor in\n  Abelian and Non-Abelian Local Gauge Field Theories","comments":"LaTeX file in Aip4-1 and Revtex4-1 style, 10 pages. v2: the words\n  \"gauge vector field(s)\" have been changed to \"gauge field(s)\" just to reflect\n  that A_\\mu is a vector in spacetime but is not a vector in the SU(N) space.\n  v3: the definition of the covariant derivative of a gauge field has been\n  clarified. v4: references updated. To the memory of Rodolfo A. Diaz, who died\n  on the 9th of April, 2016","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"PI/UAN-2015-590FT","categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The gauge field strength tensor $F_{\\mu \\nu}$ in Abelian and non-Abelian\nlocal gauge field theories is a key object in the construction of the\nLagrangian since it provides the kinetic term(s) of the gauge field(s) $A_\\mu$.\nWhen introducing this object, most of textbooks employ as a tool the commutator\nof the gauge covariant derivatives $D_\\mu \\psi$ of a fermion field $\\psi$:\n$F_{\\mu \\nu} \\psi = (i/g)[D_\\mu,D_\\nu]\\psi$. I argue that such a construction,\nalthough completely correct and valid, is not pedagogical enough for many\nstudents that approach the gauge field theories for the first time. Another\nconstruction, based on the object $D_\\mu A_\\nu$: $F_{\\mu \\nu} = D_{[\\mu}\nA_{\\nu]}$, which avoids the introduction of additional and, for the case in\nconsideration, spurious degrees of freedom such as the fermion one, simpler,\nmore pedagogical in many cases, and suitable for first-time students, is\npresented.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Dec 2015 00:03:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 5 Jan 2016 15:05:17 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 10 Apr 2016 14:15:50 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 6 Sep 2016 14:02:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-09-07"}
{"id":"1512.05202","submitter":"Ghulam Abbas","authors":"M. Zubair, G. Abbas and Ifra Noureen","title":"Possible Formation of Compact Stars in $f(R,T)$ Gravity","comments":"20 pages, 12 Figures and 1 table. Accepted for Publication in\n  Astrophysics and Space Science","journal-ref":"Astrophysics and SpaceScience 361(2016)8","doi":"10.1007/s10509-015-2596-9","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper constitutes the investigations regarding possible formation of\ncompact stars in $f(R,T)$ theory of gravity, where $R$ is Ricci scalar and $T$\nis trace of energy momentum tensor. In this connection, we use analytic\nsolution of Krori and Barua metric (Krori and Barua 1975)to spherically\nsymmetric anisotropic star in context of $f(R,T)$ gravity. The masses and radii\nof compact stars models namely model $1$, model$ 2$ and model $3$ are employed\nto incorporate with unknown constants in Krori and Barua metric. The physical\nfeatures such as regularity at center, anisotropy measure, casuality and\nwell-behaved condition of above mentioned class of compact starts are analyzed.\nMoreover, we have also discussed energy conditions, stability and surface\nredshift in $f(R,T)$ gravity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Dec 2015 10:38:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-06-28"}
